Require the Property Officer and Municipal Accountant to:

Reconcile the RPCPPE and the PPELC of accounting records to ascertain the correctness of PPE or vice versa to resolve the variance in the total amount of ₱5.756 million; 

Conduct physical count on 16 PPE items totaling ₱210.743 million;

Remove the 524 Semi-expendable items from the RPCPPE costing below 50,000.00 in the total amount of ₱9.552 million and integrate them in the Physical Count of Semi-Expendable Properties Report; 

Reclassify Semi-expendable property which were recognized as PPE to the affected appropriate semi-expendable inventory accounts (if not yet issued to end-user), expense accounts (if issued within the year), or accumulated surplus/(deficit)/retained earnings accounts (if issued in prior years) pursuant to Item 5.4.1 of COA Circular 2016-006 dated December 29, 2016;

Record all PPE items including those found at station in the Property Cards and Property Ledger Cards and to be maintained, henceforth, by the Property Unit and Accounting Unit, respectively;

Take appropriate action for the 26 PPE items which are either without cost/value/donated/not taken up as PPE;

6.1 for PPE items without cost/value, coordinate with the source agency as to the status of said PPE items, if donated, 

6.1.1 secure Invoice and Receipt of Property and other related documents supporting the transfer of PPE; and

6.1.2 ascertain cost / value based on the market/fair value or by appraisal.

6.2  for Donated PPE items to other agency, furnish a copy of an Authority from the Municipal Mayor for the donation and Invoice and Receipt of Property donated;

6.3 for PPE items found at station, reported in the RPCPPE, and not taken as PPE per accounting record, coordinate with the source agency as to the status of said PPE items, if donated, 

6.3.1 Secure Invoice and Receipt of Property and other related documents supporting the transfer of PPE; and

Prepare Journal Entry Voucher to take up the donated PPE item.

Indicate the mode of disposal of 190 unserviceable PPE and semi-expendable items in the IIRUP and the Physical Count of Semi-Expendable Properties Report, respectively; and

Invite the COA Auditor/Representative to witness the succeeding physical inventory taking in CY 2023 and years thereafter.

Require the focal person speed up the implementation of projects and justify the non-implementation of eight PPAs totaling ₱0.602 million;

Enhance monitoring activities on the implementation of PPAs funded by the National Government; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to conduct regular verification and reconciliation of unexpended balances of fund transfer and return/remit balances to source agency.

We recommended and the Management agreed to require the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer, and Municipal Budget Officer to:
Explain the basis for paying disbursements and use of funds intended for a specific PPA for another purpose as reflected in the cash deficit per SCBAA;
Justify how the cash overdraft of ₱13.132 million in the GF be resolved so that funds would be available to meet all obligations and liabilities;
Require the Local Finance Committee:
To analyze the income and expenditure patterns, and formulate and recommend fiscal plans and policies for consideration of the finance committee, as provided in Article 122 (f.2.vi) of the IRR of RA 7160, to ensure that no cash overdraft in any government funds shall be incurred at any given time of the year;
To conduct a semi-annual review and general examination of costs and accomplishments against performance standards applied in undertaking development projects pursuant to Item Article 412 (h) of the IRR of RA 7160;
Open separate depository bank accounts for the 20% DF (to include CY 2022 20% DF balances as of December 31, 2023 and the LDRRMF, to ensure funds are used solely for these purposes.

We recommended and the Management agreed to require the Property Officer and Municipal Accountant to:
Reconcile the RPCPPE and the PPELC of accounting records to ascertain the accuracy of the recorded PPE and to resolve the variance in the total amount of ₱85,538.10;
Report in the IIURP the unserviceable PPE items to reflect the actual total unserviceable items;
Facilitate the disposal of 234 unserviceable PPE items to relieve AOs of their accountabilities, to prevent further deterioration of the equipment, to decongest the storage area of the unserviceable property;
Update and tag the properties of the agency with their corresponding PAR number and ensure the reconciliation of the PAR number in the Property Sticker to the inventory records; and
Ensure that the end users of the PPE items have their copy of the Property Acknowledgement Receipt.

We recommended and the Management agreed to require the Municipal Engineer to:
Justify the excess of ₱1.028 million for disbursements of materials and labor wages paid beyond project time duration from five to 121 days over the approved cost/duration per POW;
Prepare individual POWs or sub-POWs indicating technical details for each barangay location where the PPA: Portland Cement Concrete Pavement was implemented;
Submit the latest Statement of Work Accomplishment (SWA) of the Construction of Balay Dalangpan (2023).

We recommended and the Management agreed to require the Municipal Engineer to:
Justify why only one Program of Work/PERT CPM was prepared for four (4) separate projects sites with different specifications and design;
Explain the inconsistent costing and duration per work item as reflected in the POW, PERT/CPM, and Statement of Work Accomplishment;
Prepare Individual POW/ Sub POW for each Welcome Arch in four different locations   to ascertain the corresponding cost and work duration per work item;
Justify the first partial payment of ₱2.156 million representing the 69.62 percent accomplishment per SWA as of March 1, 2023, while the accomplishment rate  is not reflective of the first nor the second revision of PERT/CPMs;
Submit the Contractor’s Request/Notices for the extension of contract time and the evaluation/approval by the Management;
Justify the 2nd revision of the contract duration to start on          December 21, 2022, which is already beyond 7 days from the NTP date, December 12, 2022.

We recommended and the Management agreed to require:
BAC and the BAC Secretariat to:
Include in the APP all APPs subject to procurement activities regardless of goods or services of any mode of procurement. If an  APP is not indicated in the APP, prepare a revise or update the APP for approval by the Municipal Mayor;
Submit the perfected Contracts and Purchase Order and supporting documents within five days upon approval for evaluation pursuant to Item 1.1 of COA Circular 2009-001, dated February 12, 2009;
For procurement through the alternative mode of procurement:
Post the RFQs in the PhilGEPS website, the webseite of the procuring entity, if available, and at any conspicuous place of the premises of the municipality;
Prepare the Abstract of Quotations setting forth the names of those who responded to the RFQ, their corresponding price quotations, and the lowest calculated quotation submitted;
Require the suppliers to submit the documents required in Appendix A of Annex H, of the IRR of RA 9184, namely, Mayor’s Permit, PhilGEPs Registration, Income/Business Tax Return, and Omnibus Sworn Statement;
Property/Supply Officer and Municipal Engineer:
Require the Property/Supply Officer/any authorized representative from the General Services Office to accept all deliveries and to affix the signature in the AIR as proof of acceptance and in the RIS for the issuance of the materials to end users;
Require the Municipal Engineer or any authorized representative to inspect only the delivered materials and affix a signature in the Inspected portion of the AIR as proof of the inspection conducted and in the RIS for the request of the materials;
Require that Delivery Receipts be dated as to the actual date of delivery of materials.

We recommended that Management agreed to:
Strengthen monitoring activities and come-up with realistic/ doable project implementation schedule;
Streamline planning and procurement activities of all infrastructure related PPAs to fast track project implementation of all on-going/ not started PPAs;
Submit the status of implementation of PPAs cited in Observation Number 2;
Refrain from programming generic PPAs, instead, consider exact PPAs that are specific, doable, and to be supported with Program of Works, the location is free from legal impediments and ready for implementation; and
Submit copies of the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) approving the implementation of PPAs totaling ₱3.812 million.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Transfer the amount of ₱324,589.80 in a separate Special Trust Fund bank account by crediting the account Trust Liability-DRRM;
Conduct reconciliation of unexpended balances of fund transfer;
Direct the LDRRMC to:
Prioritize the urgency and impact on the four (4) thematic areas of DRRM in formulating and incorporate to an updated LDRRMF Plan;
Direct the MDRRMO to:
Ensure the optimal utilization of the LDRRMF and closely monitor the implementation of approved target PPAs to effectively deliver the PPAs’ outcomes as scheduled.

